{{Expand German|date=January 2012|Emerich Coreth}}
{{Infobox person
|name = Emerich Coreth
|image =
|caption =
|birth_date = {{Birth date|1919|8|10|df=y}}
|death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|9|1|1919|8|10|df=y}}
|birth_place = [[Raabs an der Thaya]], Austria
|death_place = [[Innsbruck]], [[Austria]]
| occupation = Philosopher, priest 
}}
'''Emerich Coreth''' (10 August 1919 – 1 September 2006) was an Austrian Philosopher, Jesuit and Catholic Priest. He is well known for his works on [[metaphysics]] and [[philosophical anthropology]]. A close associate of Karl [[Rahner]], Coreth is a renowned neo-Thomist of 20th century. He was the Rector of the [[University of Innsbruck]] and the Provincial of the Austrian Province of the [[Society of Jesus]].

== Philosophy ==
Coreth specialises in [[metaphysics]], [[philosophical anthropology]], and [[history of philosophy]]. He is considered one of the philosophers who sought the creative recovery of [[Thomas Aquinas]]' metaphysics through the transcendental method introduced by [[Joseph Maréchal|Joseph Marechal]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Quest for Plausible Christian Discourse in a World of Pluralities: The Evolution of David Tracy's Understanding of "Public Theology"|last=Kim|first=Younhee|publisher=Peter Lang|year=2008|isbn=9783039107339|location=Oxford|pages=178}}</ref> Particularly, Coreth and other theologians attempted to revive the [[Philosophical realism|metaphysics of realism]] (Aristotelian-Thomistic metaphysics) by addressing the failure of [[Kantianism|Kantian philosophy]] using its presuppositions.<ref name=":0" /> One of Coreth's most important works was ''Metaphysik'' where he wrote about the Christian metaphysics of Being so that it presented a completely transcendentally reformulated version.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Being and God: A Systematic Approach in Confrontation with Martin Heidegger, Emmanuel Levinas, and Jean-Luc Marion|last=Puntel|first=Lorenz|last2=White|first2=Alan|publisher=Northwestern University Press|year=2011|isbn=9780810127708|location=Evanston, Illinois|pages=45}}</ref> This book also refuted critics such as [[Étienne Gilson|Etienne Gilson]], who argued that transcendental turn among Thomists can only lead to [[phenomenalism]] or [[idealism]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Twentieth-Century Western Philosophy of Religion 1900-2000|last=Long|first=Eugene Thomas|publisher=Kluwer Academic Publishers|year=2003|isbn=0792362853|location=Dordrecht, The Netherlands|pages=348}}</ref>  

Coreth maintained that instead of having an objective, metaphysics only has a subjective function. Here, metaphysics loses its foundation in being but Coreth said that "our a priori knowledge is metaphysical knowledge of being, which opens for us the absolute horizon of being as such."<ref name=":1" /> 

